I want you to know that I sort of understand the Jimmy Buffett delirium that you went through. In the summer of 2020, mid-covid, I worked at a dying Bed Bath & Beyond, 8 hours a day, 5-6 days a week, and then went home to sleep on a couch every night. I hated the job the entire time. For a while, any time I would go on my lunch break, I would sit in my car and listen to "It's Five O' Clock Somewhere" by Alan Jackson and Jimmy Buffett on loop for about half an hour at a time. I do not listen to country music. During these moments, I felt the spirit of Jimmy flow through my body and mind, easing all of my worries and bringing me a moment of respite. Truly, no matter what time it was, and what I was going through, it was 5 o'clock somewhere. Thanks for reminding me of the Jimmy zone.

My Mom is a massive Parrothead who has been to multiple Jimmy Buffet concerts in her lifetime.  I've had a decent portion of Jimmy Buffet's songs memorized since I was 12. I have eaten at three Margaritaville resturaunts, stayed at a Margaritaville hotel, and recently went on a Margaritaville-themed cruise ship. I have worn multiple Margaritaville shirts to school. The family minivan has a "Pirate Looks at Forty" lisence plate on the front. The bar in our basement has two Margaritaville drink coolers, a Margaritaville clock on the wall, a "Changes in Lattitues" sign, and an "It's 5-o'clock Somewhere" sign right above it, and multiple Margaritaville margarita blenders. Our dog has a Land Shark branded life jacket. I own a Margaritaville bike with a little squeaky parrot instead of a bell or horn. I have read four of Jimmy Buffet's books, including two childrens picture books and two short story collections inspired by his songs. My mother's ringtone has been "Margaritaville" the song since she got her first iPhone and I've been conditioned to think her phone is ringing every time I hear that song in the wild. She also wants to move to Florida and live at the Margaritaville Resort outside of Orlando, and wants her gravestone to be a palm tree with lyrics from "The Weather is Here" engraved on it. I also know way too much Jimmy Buffett trivia for someone my age, including his birthday and the stories behind some of his songs.  Did I mention I'm not even of drinking age?  As someone who's been surrounded by Jimmy Buffet shit my whole life, it is utterly fascinating seeing the opinion of an outsider. Yes, the Parrotheads are a cult, even as an insider I can tell you that, but if I had to be born into a cult, I'm glad it was this one.  RIP Jimmy Buffett. You made my childhood, for better or for worse

I am sixty-two years old and have been listening to Buffett since the early days. Growing up on the beach in Florida, my friends and I couldn't get enough of Buffett, and by the mid eighties, I had seen him in concert a couple of times. Both times, the shows were just ok and nothing to write home about, so I never went to another concert even though he toured our city every few years. From 1990-1995, I worked in Key West Florida, so of course, I beat a path to Margaritaville when I first arrived, and I do have to say the Burger was pretty good, but the service was horrible! I only went a few times after that, usually when friends would visit, and of course, they all wanted to hit Margaritaville first. Each time the service sucked and the last time I went into the Margaritaville in Key West, my friends and I got so tired of waiting to get served that we got up and left. I've been to two other Margaritavilles, and both of those establishments were ok on the service (hardly any customers),  so it's not hard to get service. The food was god-awful at those locations. I  think Jimmy Buffett was all about cashing in on his fame because without his name and popularity, those restaurants would have closed long ago. I can't imagine now that he has passed away that the restaurants across the country will remain open.

I went to a single Margaritaville. It was in Jamaica. What boggles my mind about all these American Margaritavilles is the contrast between the ones that are outside of the country and the ones in the US is how different the tone is. In Jamaica, and all the others in the Carribean, there is a pool. You can drink a margarita and waste away in a lounge chair all day. You basically go there and find the same experience the song describes. The bar opens when the cruise ships come in, and close when the tourists leave.   Margaritaville isn't Hard Rock Cafe. It feels like they are trying to be though. It just doesn't make sense. Hard Rock Cafe is a place that specializes burgers around a collection of rock-and-roll memorabilia. It works in any big 'hip' city. Margaritaville... not so much.

Comments caused me to do the math; in terms of gimmick restaurants Medieval Times wold be short but mostly a lost cause since that just covers the same areas as Margaritaville and Rainforest Cafe, while Hard Rock Cafe would be the first chance to visit the Pacific Northwest since it has a Washington location, and Bubba Gump Shrimp Company would be absolutely hellish but would take them through Colorado and Minnesota, places I assume they haven't been. Both of them have more than 20 locations, though, with Hard Rock at 27 and Bubba Gump at 22, so I wouldn't wish that on human beings. and places like Ruby's Diner, Johnny Rockets, Outback Steakhouse, and Cracker Barrel are, while still gimmick restaurants, just so high in number that you can't ever do them all.  Here's a dark horse candidate though: Hamburger Mary's, a chain of restaurants each themed after their local gay community, with 17 locations in California, Texas, Colorado, Florida, Missouri, Wisconsin, Nevada, and Ohio. Doable trip, small number of locations, got character, and apparently it's pseudo-local so the food might be varied!

But you didnâ€™t go to the margaritaville in Jacksonville Florida so you really did not go to them allâ€¦ FRAUDS!
So I live in Ocean Springs, next door to Biloxi, MS. The initial opening of the Margaritaville Casino was met with a lot of fanfare. People were really looking forward to having it on the coast. That location initially included the "volcano segment" you witnessed, but it was somewhat different. In the casino, the volcano was a mere prop, and every hour or so, Buffet's "Volcano" song would play, followed by flashing lights and a rumbling noise. Then, a woman would slide down into a pool close to the bar of the Margaritaville restaurant, then sit on a metal hoop that would twirl in the air as she waved to people while "Margaritaville" played. I went a couple times in its initial year of being open, but from day one, there were two things that really weren't going to bode well for the property. One, its location. The beach along the MS Gulf Coast is prime real estate, but some casinos are off the main strip along Highway 90 and are successful. However, that's because they've been around long enough that they have a stable following (Boomtown, IP Casino), or they're easily visible (Scarlet Pearl). Margaritaville was a very small casino built behind a Harrah's and Palace Casino with no clear signage directing patrons to their location, tucked away almost as if it were a dirty secret. Two, lack of amenities. The Margaritaville Casino was built without a hotel. The closest options for lodging around their casino were other casinos. Honestly, I feel the only reason Margaritaville as a casino in Biloxi lasted for two years was because of the fact they were a Margaritaville, but they finally closed that location down, moved Margaritaville to a new location on the beach itself, and changed to the more family-friendly venue you saw. The "Volcano" sequence was brought over, but because it was now an arcade and not a casino, they removed the bikini-clad woman sequence and replaced it with the volcano burping instead. The worst part of that is that it happens every 45 minutes or so while you're there.

In a world often fraught with stress and routine, there exists an oasis of bliss where time stands still and worries melt away. Margaritaville, the famed restaurant inspired by the legendary Jimmy Buffett, has transcended mere culinary delights to become a life-altering pilgrimage for many. This paradisiacal haven has the power to touch the soul, bringing forth a transformation akin to the Second Coming of Christ.  Stepping foot into Margaritaville is akin to entering a mystical realm, one where the boundaries between reality and fantasy blur, and everyday life fades into insignificance. The ambiance alone is intoxicating, with vibrant hues that transport patrons to the sunny shores of a Caribbean paradise. The whimsical decor and laid-back atmosphere evoke a sense of carefree euphoria, all thanks to the visionary mind of Jimmy Buffett.  Speaking of Buffett, it is hard to overlook the profound impact this troubadour has had on humanity. His music, filled with themes of escapism, island life, and the pursuit of happiness, has touched the lives of millions. He is, without a doubt, a prophet of joy and serenity. His ability to craft melodies that resonate with the soul is unparalleled, and his lyrics serve as guiding principles for a life of tranquility and harmony.  At Margaritaville, the spirit of Jimmy Buffett is palpable, as if he is present in each margarita served, each verse played by the band, and each delectable dish that graces the tables. It is as if the man himself has blessed this establishment with his divine wisdom, transforming it into a temple of self-discovery and rejuvenation.  One cannot underestimate the profound effect this place has on those who enter its hallowed doors. Countless patrons have emerged from Margaritaville with a newfound lease on life, a spark of inspiration that propels them toward their dreams and passions. For some, it is the catalyst that pushes them to embrace a more carefree and adventurous lifestyle, casting aside the shackles of monotony in favor of a life well-lived.  The staff at Margaritaville, too, play an integral role in this spiritual awakening. Their warm smiles and genuine hospitality create an atmosphere of acceptance and camaraderie, as if everyone is part of one big island family. It is this unity, this connection among strangers, that solidifies the belief in Jimmy Buffett as the pinnacle of humanityâ€”an artist who has transcended his music to foster a worldwide community bound by the pursuit of happiness.  In conclusion, Margaritaville is more than a restaurant; it is a transformative pilgrimage, a sacred retreat, and an ode to the prophetic genius of Jimmy Buffett. It awakens the dormant dreams within us and reminds us that life is too short not to live it with passion and authenticity. So, if you seek a spiritual revival and desire to experience the Second Coming of Christ-like rejuvenation, venture into Margaritaville and embrace the gospel of Jimmy Buffett. Your life will never be the same again.

I've had two of the best dining experiences of my life at two of the three Margaritavilles I've visited.  One was at the Navy Pier in Chicago where we had an extremely flamboyant, gay, black, Southern waiter who told us a fake story about a customer's eye falling out onto the table and was impressed that my mom had apparently eaten a full plate of nachos by herself (we had all shared it, actually). The other was on Duval Street in Key West on my mom's 50th birthday, which was JULY 2020, and we sat in the table with an open window onto the street. The live musician (whose name was David Bryce Warren) played Cotton-Eyed Joe and Happy Birthday for my mom, and everyone in the restaurant ended up celebrating my mom's birthday with us, and people on the street kept wishing her a happy birthday too. She remembers that as her best birthday ever.

Fun fact about the Biloxi Margaritaville Resort from someone who lived in that area! That entire greenspace visible at 14:32 was actually supposed to be part of an even BIGGER resort. The original plan was to make a GIGANTIC complex with artificial rainforests, a shopping mall, a theme park, etc etc. They broke ground on it, and even built a few bits of frame/beams, only to run out of money. The construction site stayed vacant for so so SO long before they eventually tore it down.  Eventually, the casino across the street took over part of the area, and decided to turn a big chunk of the site into the greenspace it is today. There's a little concert venue on it, and also a restaurant on one of its borders.  And in the meantime, they decided they wanted to open a much MUCH smaller Margaritaville casino (the one picture at 15:00 ), this time on the back bay. They constructed it, and it stayed open for just a little bit before it too, closed down. I managed to go once, and there was almost no one there, despite the fact that it had recently opened.   And THEN lol, at some point they decided to just convert the pre-existing building shown at 14:32 to a Margaritaville Hotel/Resort. It was a building that was standing vacant for years and years; it was a skeleton of a casino leftover from Katrina. You can even see the old sign frames atop it (that for some reason they STILL haven't gotten rid of or converted to anything).   That of course was the one to stick, because they've expanded outward to include the little outdoor theme park, and have been chugging along ever since! I also find it very interesting because it's one of the few resorts, if not the ONLY resort on the MS Gulf Coast to not have a casino (which is even more interesting when you consider that what it tried to be...TWICE lol). It's instead more family-oriented, what with its giant arcade, its restaurant, its big pool, and its theme park.  Soooo yeah lol! It just has an insane history, and so it was awesome to see in this video as someone who's watched all its ups and downs lol! Also, love the arcade getting the proper hype because it is indeed MASSIVE.

Holy crap, The Thing attraction has come a long way.  When I went, it was 3 or 4 ramshackle metal sheds behind the gas station with no unifying theme.  There were no dinosaurs or aliens, but they had an 1800s pistol and a letter the owner had sent a loved one about killing Indians.  There was an amateur log carved diorama of a medieval torture chamber from a local (contemporary) artist.  They had a junked car Bonnie and Clyde had allegedly used, and it just kind of went on like that until it anticlimactically ended with The Thing, which just sat in a hip high graffiti etched box with a glass top.  It had a plaque, but none of the production shown here.  Each shack had rattlesnake warnings posted at the open doors, and the whole thing cost 1 dollar.  No air conditioning outside the giftshop.

You're actually mistaken concerning the Biloxi Margaritaville Casino. The Casino was highly profitable, but that was all that it was a casino. Buffet wanted to add a resort hotel to it, but they were leasing the land, and when the land owner said no and raised the rates on the land, Margaritaville said fine and shut down. Basically the land owner was purposely blocking the financing which had already been lined up for the expansion in hopes of squeezing more money out of the company. So they bought the land the resort sits on now, and there is still hope that they will one day add the Casino back where the arcade now is.  I've been to that Casino several times and it was always packed.

My only experience with Margaritaville was on a vacation on the island of Cozumel in Mexico.  Our group of 4 had just arrived and we decided to walk from the resort into town instead of taking a cab.  It seemed pretty close and we were sick of sitting through the shuttle, cab, and plane rides to get us there.  Well we were not used the 90 degree heat and sun, and it was a 2 mile walk out in the open.  When we finally reached the edge of town, the first and only place we saw was JIMMY BUFFET'S MARGARITAVILLE blasting Jimmy's 80's hits out the front door and looking very much like it had shade, drinks, and bathrooms.  Greatest restaurant ever, and nothing will convince me otherwise.

Hey Eddie, just wanted to give some info on the Tulsa location you visited. The casino (including hotel) are owned by the Native Americans, the Muscogee Nation. Margaritaville is simply an attraction for the casino, hence the signage about luck with all the sharks and such. The characters you mentioned are actually mascots of the various games in the casino. Mr Money Bags, Lucky Duck, and Ruby Red to name a few. I'm glad that location was a good one!

So I grew up in Charleston South Carolina and my mom, her friend, her friend's daughter, and I would go to Mrytle Beach for day trips every once and a while. Well my mom and her friend are big country music fans and of course love margaritas lol. So they ALWAYS wanted to go to Margaritaville. Well, when I was a kid I was super shy and anxious (I'm still anxious lmao) and Margaritaville scared the sh^t out of me. Why? The f^cking hurricane drink mixer. Growing up in South Carolina, hurricanes were very scary so obviously a hurricane simulating drink mixer in a restaurant was very scary to a small child with anxiety. My mom didn't really understand the whole anxiety thing back then so they always wanted to try and convince me to go to the restaurant. Nah, I screamed and cried and we never went. The first time I set foot in that restaurant and actually was ok with it was when I was TEN YEARS OLD. And I still hated the hurricane drink mixer, but at least I was able to sit down and enjoy the meal. If that wasn't a warning sign that I have an anxiety disorder, I don't know what was ğŸ˜­ My mom definitely understands now and feels bad about how insistent she was on going to f^cking Margaritaville lol

Hey there, Syracuse native here. I actually work at the movie theater in the mall that the Syracuse Margaritaville is in and can offer some insight.  1: Destiny USA is not doing great in 2023. It's still the 4th biggest mall in America and popular, but Covid and (frequent) violent crimes occurring at it definitely hurt it financially. 2: The main clientele for the Syracuse Margaritaville is *very* old people. At least once a week I have an elderly couple turn up to my movie theater to ask for directions to the Margaritaville. 3: Your comments about the Margaritaville being "lifeless" and "easily the worst" ring true of Syracuse as a whole. We've got a very thriving local culture but we all wish we were somewhere else.  Regardless, great video! If you ever find yourself in Syracuse again and want to risk getting stabbed or shot, swing by the movie theater in Destiny and say hi.

This is so cool
I worked as a prep cook at a Margaritaville and I cannot express how wild it was to hear the jammin' jambalaya get this kind of shout-out. I don't eat meat so I can't speak to the taste, but it took one cook an entire shift just to mise. If you put two cooks on it during the day you could PROBABLY get a batch done. I worked nights solo and I lived in abject fear of the words "jambalaya on the fly." When my shift supervisor checked me out at the end of the night, every time without fail he would open my meticulously cleaned tilt skillet and say "oh no, it's full of jambalaya!" just to watch me squirm. I had a running joke with a coworker where our response to any sort of hardship was to drop to our knees and yell "JAMBALAYA!!" at the sky. It's been almost five years and it is still the stuff of my nightmares. I couldn't have asked for a better final boss for this video.

I live in Pigeon Forge, so I spent half the video excited to see how you portrayed this cryptic tourist hellzone. Specifically, I was excited to see if you mentioned something that I affectionately call Ass Monkey, which you showed the front of at 37:27. I call him that because from the back, you can only see his ass, which they made caked up for some fucking reason. Just because it's funny, I've made it my personal goal to make all of my online friends see it in person at some point.  It was also just wild to see someone I watch be in my area and show footage of it, shit's nuts  Also, the entertainment center thing the Pigeon Forge Margaritaville is in is called The Island. It shares a tram system with a convention center, the Leconte Center, which hosts an anime/gaming/cosplay convention called Yamacon every December. My favorite part of going is seeing all the Margaritaville tourists stuck on the tram and forced to look at all of the cosplayers. Almost all of them look at the cosplayers as if they need to be crucified. I recommend visiting the area if you want a show like that lmao

Growing up in Florida and with Jimmy Buffet being a constant in my childhood means that the first section of this video made me laugh and feel weirdly nostalgic (one of the Margaritavilles you went to was in my hometown!!!). When I was a little kid, the food quality at these restaurants used to actually be pretty good and my whole family would scarf down Cheeseburgers in Paradise like our lives depended on it. But then Jimmy Buffet sold the brand to some other company and the quality went down which is unfortunate. If you're ever back in Florida you should try the Lulu's restaurants which are named and owned by Jimmy Buffet's sister. Although it is still beachy tourist food, the quality is much better (presumedly because it wasn't bought out). I especially recommend their nachos, smoothies, fried chicken, and any salad with their homemade dressing. Plus there's only a few of them so you won't have to torture yourself to get there.  Also fun fact: Jimmy's plane in Citywalk Orlando was actually shot down by the Jamaican government because they thought he was smuggling drugs and instead of getting mad, Jimmy wrote a song about it and you can still see the bullet holes on the plane if you know where to look

Last Christmas Eve the weather got so bad at my house that we lost power and by extension, water (we have well water). So for Christmas (Eve), my family booked a hotel in Pigeon Forge (Tennessee's equivilent to Orlando, Florida) and spent Christmas Eve and Christmas there were we would have power and limitless showers. After everyone took a shower we went to find a place to eat, and decided on Margaritaville because everyone agreed that it would be funny. Upon arriving at the Margaritaville after navigating terrible traffic and an even worse road and parkinglot layout, we approached the Margaritaville to discover that minutes before we showed up, the watermain connection to the building had burst and the entire resturant was actively flooding. First of all, I am from Florida and the rain IS a big deal. You're so valid for that.   So, last year I was a Universal Orlando season pass holder, and my friends and I have this entire like, cult following for the Cat in the Hat ride. There were 5 of us total which is exactly how many adults you can squeeze into that fever dream. I'm here to tell you 1. they actually nerfed the part where the cart sort of whips you around recentlyâ€”it used to be a harsher motion (I guess someone had issues on it? Unclear) and 2. absolutely nothing could have hit home more for me that seeing you highlight something so stupid and weird that managed to become so personal to me and my best friends.   I adore these long-form roadtrip videos. They perfectly capture so many things that feel intrinsically American, for good or ill (and maybe there are other places with the same vibe! I can only speak to my own experiences). They're just an honest slice of what extended travel is like through huge chunks of the country, and a lot of it is draining and inconvenient and awful, but a lot of it is cryptic billboards leading to even more cryptic museums, and gas station-theme park hybrids, and random King Kong statues in the middle of Tennessee.   To call this type of video a love letter to road trips or Americana or consumerism or any of that would feel inaccurate, but so would saying there's no element of that in them. There's just something that to me is very beautiful about seeing the experiences I've had mirrored even partially in someone else's life. Cat in the Hat, the statues in Pigeon Forge, even the Florida rain storms.   I'm not sure why the Margaritaville Video has me waxing poetic on a Thursday night, but I think Jimmy would think it's alright.   P.S. I love Ted casually rocking a "The Thing?" shirt at 36:52

jimmy buffet for president
Your next video adventure awaits: Every international Margaritaville. The best part!? You can take a cruise ship to all of them! The Bahamas, Cozumel, and Jamaica await you, and many routes even go to Key West, so a re-visit is in order. And if you want to go even bigger... Head over to the islands of Maui and Oaha in Hawaii to experience the fake Cheeseburger in Paradise (aka "cheeseburger nation/cheeseburger restaurants)... They're so fake that Jimmy Buffet sued their pants off when they first opened, but somehow they still exist. I lived in Lahaina, Hawaii, and worked at the flagship location on front street...I was a host. I'm a 6'4" 240 pound bearded dude that had to wear a plastic hula skirt and say "aloha" to every single customer. If I had a dollar for every sarcastic "nice skirt" comment tossed my way, I could buy the entire Margaritaville empire myself, and still have money to spare for my own plane. The place is bananas off-the-walls busy at all times, and they make strong Mai Tais. They have live music, but due to the terms of the lawsuit, the live musicians cannot legally play any Jimmy Buffet song, even if tipped gobs of money to do so. One musician played a guitar solo behind his back like Jimi Hendrix for an entire song, and didn't miss a note. It was the best live performance I've ever seen, and I've seen Radiohead live. It's a wonderful place... Go there, now.

If you want a proper Perfect Margarita (which is a specific type of margarita, like a Tommy's Margarita) use 2oz of a good blanco tequila like TapatÃ­o, 1.5oz fresh squeezed lime juice, .5oz good triple sec like Cointreau, and 2 dashes Angostura bitters. Salted rim on the glass is optional but you can also add a small pinch of salt to your cocktail shaker which is my preferred method. Strain into a chilled coupe glass and you've got yourself one of the best tequila cocktails to ever exist.
